Baker Cloud Console (CE) and REST API

  • created: 11/30/2013
  • latest update: 11/30/2013
  • by: NIN9 Creative, LLC
  • email: info@bakerframework.com

Baker Cloud Console (CE) is an Open Source complement to Baker that extends the basic functionality of the framework with additions such as a full web based administration interface with database backend, REST API and more in order to support full functionality for Free and Paid Subscriptions and Issues.

Before you Begin

Thanks for downloading Baker Cloud Console (CE)! 

Baker Cloud Console (CE) is a complete solution for enabling a robust server side backend to complement the Baker Framework.  For release 1.1, Baker Cloud Console (CE) will fully support all required features to enable both Paid In-App Purchases and Paid Subscriptions for the Baker 4.2 release.

This help documentation will walk you through setting up your Baker Cloud Console (CE) and API installation.

For reference, the following diagram depicts the components required for this implementation.  As you can see, there is an API layer that is used by the iOS Shelf application that acts as a broker to the backend database as well as the Apple Receipt Validation API.  The administration website is used to configure and maintain the data in the DB which is then consumed by the Shelf via the API.  Pretty straightforward!

Components

  1. Your branded Baker iOS Newsstand Application
  2. MySQL database
  3. Baker Cloud Console (CE) API layer
  4. Baker Cloud Console (CE) Administration Console

Prerequisites

You will need a hosting account that supports the following minimum requirements.

  • PHP 5.3 or greater.  The Slim Framework used for the API requires 5.3 or greater.
  • MySQL

We will assume a pattern of using 2 multiple subdomains for setting up the two server based components.  You can set these up however you like, but we are only going to deal with this variation in the documentation for simplicity.

  • http://api.yourdomain.com  -  where the API will be installed
  • http://app.yourdomain.com  -  where the administration console website will be installed

Please note that there are two separate frameworks being used by Baker Cloud Console (CE).  We are using both the amazing CodeIgniter Framework for the Administration Console as well as the Slim Framework for the API.  Both of these frameworks represent (in our opinion) the best frameworks for building upon.  There are active communities supporting both and they are easy to use and understand.  They are both based on PHP and coupled with the MYSQL database are a common platform that you can easily setup on most LAMP (Linux, Apache, MySQL, PHP) web hosting accounts.

While you might be able to get away with using a shared webhosting provider, we recommend using a VPS (Virtual Private Server).  If your Newsstand magazine is popular, you might soon find yourself in a bind with a shared hosting account.  We recommend Knownhost , WiredTree or Digital Ocean! Do check them out and use the links if you decide to sign up.  Yes we do get a tiny bit of affiliate earnings, but hey you didn't pay anything for Baker Cloud Console (CE)! :)

 

MySQL Database Setup

The first step in setting up Baker Cloud Console (CE) is to create an empty MySQL database.  This database will house the tables necessary for both the API and Cloud Console.  The steps required for setting up the database differ from web host to web host.  If you require help in setting up the database portion of this installation - your best bet is to contact your web host or view their help documentation on MySQL databases.

  1. Use your webhost's control panel to create a new MySQL database.
  2. Create a new database user that has FULL access to the MySQL database.
  3. Make note of the following items:  DB Name, DB Username, DB Password

For this documentation we are going to assume that our database information was setup as follows:

Database Name:  bakerc_cloudce

Username:  bakerc_ce

Password:  baker

At this point you should have a blank database with a username and password.  When you install the Baker Cloud Console (CE), it will automatically add the required database tables and sample data.

Cloud Console Install

Installing the Baker Cloud Console (CE) should be fairly straightforward.  We've built an installer that executes as part of the setup that will connect to the database that you setup in the previous installation step and automatically create the necessary database tables as well as sample data...  You're welcome!

 

1.  Create a Subdomain (or folder location)

Create a subdomain on your webhosting account for whatever domain name you have or prefer.  You can also set this application up in a subfolder, however because of the way that CodeIgniter works, it might be simpler to use a subdomain.  Here we will use http://app.yourdomain.com

 

2.  DB Configuration Settings

You will need to edit the following file.  bakercloud-ce-console/source/application/config/database.php and modify the settings to match your configuration settings created in the MySQL Database Setup step.  In most cases you can use localhost for the hostname.  However we've seen some instances where the webhost requires something different to be setup.  If you run into issues with the hostname, double check with your webhost.  Example "mysqlinstance.myhost.com:3306" where a qualified hostname and port are required.

$db['default']['hostname'] = 'localhost';           // for pdo: mysql:host=localhost
$db['default']['username'] = 'bakerc_ce';           // DB Username
$db['default']['password'] = 'baker';               // DB Username Password
$db['default']['database'] = 'bakerc_cloudce';      // DB Name
$db['default']['dbdriver'] = 'mysqli';
$db['default']['dbprefix'] = '';
$db['default']['pconnect'] = TRUE;
$db['default']['db_debug'] = TRUE;
$db['default']['cache_on'] = FALSE;
$db['default']['cachedir'] = '';
$db['default']['char_set'] = 'utf8';
$db['default']['dbcollat'] = 'utf8_general_ci';
$db['default']['swap_pre'] = '';
$db['default']['autoinit'] = TRUE;
$db['default']['stricton'] = FALSE;

3.  Copy the Source Files

Using a FTP client, copy the contents of the bakercloud-ce-console/source folder to the root of the subdomain or folder you created in Step 1.

 

4.  Run Baker Cloud Console (CE) Installer

After you've copied the Baker Cloud Console (CE) source files to your website, you will need to now run the installer.

Fire up a web browser and navigate to your Baker Cloud Console (CE) install.  Since we used http://app.yourdomain.com, let's pretend that is where we are headed to.  When you navigate to your install location, the following page should load provided you've done everything right up to this point.

 

Make sure that you make the Config Folder writable.  You can do this via your FTP program.  The installer will warn you and won't let you continue until this is correctly configured.  For the install to run, it generally seems that you need to give 777 flags to the folder.  You should be able to change this to 775 after the installation is complete.  Also, if your database credentials are not correct you may get another error - or the page might not even load.  So double check that as well.

If you've got everything correct, you should be able to hit Install Baker Cloud Console (CE) v1.1

If everything worked you will see the following page.

 

 

5.  Done!  Baker Cloud Console (CE) Login

If you get to the confirmation page, you can now login to Baker Cloud Console (CE) with the username and default password given.

Username:  user

Password:  123456

The login page will look like this.  You should be able to successfully log in.

 

6.  Dashboard View After Logging In

If everything is setup correctly, after logging in you should see the following Baker Cloud Console (CE) Dashboard page.

7.  Baker Cloud Console (CE) Installation Complete

This step of the installation is now complete.  Next up is installing the REST API layer.  It's much easier to do, so let's get to that now.

Setting up your own publications should be pretty straightforward.  However if you have issues you can head on over to the GitHub Repository to ask questions.

 

 

API Install

Installing the Baker Cloud Console (CE) REST API layer is a bit simpler than the Cloud Console, so let's get to it!

 

1.  Create a Subdomain (or folder location)

Create a subdomain on your webhosting account for whatever domain name you have or prefer.  You can also set this application up in a subfolder, however be careful as the two frameworks may conflict with each other if you set this up in a nonstandard manner.  Here we will use http://api.yourdomain.com

 

2.  DB Configuration Settings

You will need to edit the following file.  bakercloud-ce-api/index.php and modify the settings to match your configuration settings created in the MySQL Database Setup step.  In most cases you can use localhost for the hostname.  However we've seen some instances where the webhost requires something different to be setup.  If you run into issues with the hostname, double check with your webhost.  Example "mysqlinstance.myhost.com:3306" where a qualified hostname and port are required.

// Baker Cloud Console (CE) REST API SETUP CONFIGURATION SETTING
// ************************************************************
$dbContainer['db.options'] = array(
    'host' => 'localhost',                    // CONFIGURE TO YOUR DB HOSTNAME                    
    'username' => 'bakerc_ce',                // CONFIGURE TO YOUR DB USERNAME        
    'password' => 'baker',                    // CONFIGURE TO YOUR DB USERNAME'S PASSWORD
    'dbname' => 'bakerc_cloudce'              // CONFIGURE TO YOUR DB INSTANCE NAME
);
//*************************************************************

 

3.  Copy the Source Files

Using an FTP client, copy the contents of the bakercloud-ce-api folder to the root of the subdomain or folder you created in Step 1.  Be sure to copy the .htaccess file at the root.  If you use a standard FTP client, you should be able to see this file and not miss it.

 

3.  Test Install

Fire up your web browser and head on over to your api install location.  Here we assume http://api.yourdomain.com

If everything was setup correctly and you have the correct version of PHP running (>= 5.3) then you should get the following webpage being displayed.

 

 

4.  Check DB Connectivity

Click on the link under the Get Started section to validate your DB connectivity to the Baker Cloud Console (CE) database.  If everything is correct, you will get a success message - otherwise you'll probably see some sort of error.

 

 

You can also test your install by navigating to the following URL (obviously change it to match your install config).

 

http://api.yourdomain.com/issues/com.nin9creative.baker/B7340733-CC87-420B-888A-EA24776E276A

 

If you did everything correct, you should see a JSON response similar to this.

 

 

7.  Baker Cloud Console (CE) REST API Install Complete

Congratulations!  This completes the server side setup of Baker Cloud Console (CE).  The next section will talk about the configuration changes required in your iOS Baker Newsstand Application in order to get it working with the Baker Cloud Console (CE) Backend!

Please note.  The successful setup and end to end testing of both your iOS Baker Newsstand Application and Baker Cloud Console (CE) is a bit tricky.  There is a lot of help material on the Baker Github Repository regarding iTunes Connect and Newsstand settings.  You should head over there if you are having issues getting your Newsstand settings correct on the Apple side of things.

Baker 4.2+ Setup

As mentioned a bit earlier in the API Install section, much of the setup for iTunes Connect and the Apple side of Subscriptions and In-App Purchases are outlined in the official Baker project documentation and Github Repository.

There are various Constants and settings that need to be changed in the Baker distribution in order for Baker to communicate with the Baker Cloud Console (CE) backend.

After you've pulled down the Baker source, open the project in Xcode and navigate to the following file.

Baker | BakerShelf/Constants.h

You will find a section called BAKER_NEWSSTAND.  If you examine the code below, you will see where you will need to make changes.  Replace the domain name with the endpoint that you set up for your specific Baker Cloud Console (CE) installation.

The following sections are important for MagRocket, and point back to the MagRocket API endpoints.

  • NEWSSTAND_MANIFEST_URL
  • PURCHASE_CONFIRMATION_URL
  • PURCHASES_URL
  • POST_APNS_TOKEN_URL (only necessary if you are going to support Push Notifications)

Obviously you will also need to correctly set your AUTO_RENEWABLE_SUBSCRIPTION_PRODUCT_IDS as well to correspond to your specific iTunes setup for Baker.

 

    #ifdef BAKER_NEWSSTAND

        // Remove the following line once you complete the Newsstand setup below.
        #warning Newsstand: Remember to set the AppStore/Newsstand constants and delete this line once you did it.

        // ----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
        // Mandatory - This constant defines where the JSON file containing all the publications is located.
        // For more information on this file, see: https://github.com/bakerframework/baker/wiki/Newsstand-shelf-JSON
        // E.g. @"http://example.com/shelf.json"
        #define NEWSSTAND_MANIFEST_URL @"http://api.yourdomain.com/issues/:app_id/:user_id"

        // ----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
        // Optional - This constant specifies the URL to ping back when a user purchases an issue or a subscription.
        // For more information, see: https://github.com/bakerframework/baker/wiki/Baker-Server-API
        // E.g. @"http://example.com/purchased"
        #define PURCHASE_CONFIRMATION_URL @"http://api.yourdomain.com/confirmpurchase/:app_id/:user_id"

        // ----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
        // Optional - This constant specifies a URL that will be used to retrieve the list of purchased issues.
        // For more information, see: https://github.com/bakerframework/baker/wiki/Baker-Server-API
        // E.g. @"http://example.com/purchases"
        #define PURCHASES_URL @"http://api.yourdomain.com/purchases/:app_id/:user_id"

        // ----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
        // Optional - This constant specifies the URL to ping back when a user enables push notifications.
        // For more information, see: https://github.com/bakerframework/baker/wiki/Baker-Server-API
        // E.g. @"http://example.com/post_apns_token"
        #define POST_APNS_TOKEN_URL @"http://api.yourdomain.com/apns/:app_id/:user_id"

        // ----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
        // Mandatory - The following two constants identify the subscriptions you set up in iTunesConnect.
        // See: iTunes Connect -> Manage Your Application -> (Your application) -> Manage In App Purchases
        // You *have* to set at least one among FREE_SUBSCRIPTION_PRODUCT_ID and AUTO_RENEWABLE_SUBSCRIPTION_PRODUCT_IDS.

        // This constant identifies a free subscription.
        // E.g. @"com.example.MyBook.subscription.free"
        #define FREE_SUBSCRIPTION_PRODUCT_ID @""

        // This constant identifies one or more auto-renewable subscriptions.
        // E.g.:
        // #define AUTO_RENEWABLE_SUBSCRIPTION_PRODUCT_IDS [NSArray arrayWithObjects: 
        //     @"com.example.MyBook.subscription.3months", 
        //     @"com.example.MyBook.subscription.6months", 
        //     nil]
        #define AUTO_RENEWABLE_SUBSCRIPTION_PRODUCT_IDS [NSArray arrayWithObjects: 
               @"com.nin9creative.baker.sub.6month", 
               @"com.nin9creative.baker.sub.1year", 
               nil]

    #endif

 

Quick Start Tips

As you probably imagine, getting all of the pieces aligned with Apple, Baker, and Baker Cloud Console (CE) is a bit tough as there are a lot of moving parts.

After you get everything setup, we advise that you take a look at the sample data that is bundled with the Baker Cloud Console (CE) install which provides a sample Publication with a handfull of Issues also setup.

It should be pretty straightforward once you look at it, but there are a few things that need explanation.

 

1.  Publication Setup

If you navigate to Publication Management / Publication you will see the following record.

 

 

Click on the blue "Edit" button to view the details for the Publication.

 

 

As you notice there are a few different fields here that are important.

iTunes Shared Secret  -  This field is required.  You can generate or view the iTunes Shared Secret key from your iTunes Connect settings for your iOS Baker Application.  In order to make the testing work, this is required.

Subscription Behavior - This is a flag that indicates the Issue "unlocking" behavior for your publication.  If you select "Unlock All Issues", when a user purchases a subscription all Issues for that publication will be unlocked for Issues that fall within their Subscription Term and before their Subscription Term.  This basically equates to all future issues falling within the terms of their subscription as well as all "back" issues.  If you select "Unlock Only Issues Within Subscription Term" - only the Issues that are released during the months that the Paid Subscription term is valid will be unlocked.

***Because the Sandbox accellerates time, a 6 month subscription is only valid for 30 minutes (5 minutes for each month of subscription length).  Baker Cloud Console (CE) tracks and makes issues available to the end user based on the start and end date of their valid subscription.  As you can imagine - you wouldn't be able to test your application with a 30 minute span for available issues.  When operating against the Sandbox this behavior is ignored and all available issues are marked as downloadable and available - allowing ease of testing.

Development Mode?  -  This is an internal flag with Baker Cloud Console (CE) that adds additional logging to the SYSTEM_LOG.  In past releases it affected the iTunes API Level, however in this current release there is a separate indicator for selecting the "Sandbox" or "Production" for your Publication.

iTunes Cache Duration - Because the API call to the Apple Receipt validations service often takes 3-5 seconds to complete, Baker Cloud Console (CE) caches the results of the Receipt Validation and only re-checks it after a specified duration.  Generally it's fine to leave this at 12 hours.

iTunes API Level - iTunes Receipt Validation service endpoint.  Sandbox is for development, testing and while in Application Review with Apple.  Production is for once your application is live on the App Store.

Issue Security?  -  This is an optional setting that generates a intermediate URL for your Issues list.  When a user tries to download an issue with Issue Security turned on, the API does a lookup and validates that there is still an active subscription and/or the user has the appropriate rights to download the issue in question.  This is not required, however it might be good practice to keep this enabled once your application goes into production.  If you leave it off, the URL for your HPUB content will be sent back in the Issues list and Baker will just download that HPUB directly if the "Download" button is enabled within Baker for the issue.

For example, a non secure Issue download link might look like this.

http://www.bakercontent.com/publication/com.nin9creative.baker/samplemagazine.hpub

A secure issue download link might look like this.  The user and issue are validated for the publication prior to allowing the download.

http://api.yourdomain.com/issue/com.nin9creative.baker/B7340733-CC87-420B-888A-EA24776E276A/BakerMagazine-January

 

2.  Issue Management

Issues are defined with all of the same required parameters as the original Baker Shelf JSON file.

Click on Publication Management / Issues to view the sample issues bundled with the Baker Cloud Console (CE) installation.

 

 

Let's click on the BakerMagazine-January issue to take a look.  Click on the blue "Edit" button for that issue.  The data that you will see for the issue should look pretty straightforward.  Of course the variable settings are where your cover and HPUB urls are located.  Those are up to you to upload and validate reachability.  Baker Cloud Console (CE) only stores the URL pointers to the actual files.  This allows you flexibility in where you store your actual HPUB and other assets.  You can use your own hosting server or something like Amazon S3 if you so desire.
